ADMINISTRATIVE_ALREADY_REIMBURSED__C: The Town's Connections website has data sources available to the public. The Town partners with many nonprofits in the community to aid outreach and awareness.
BEHAVIORAL_HEALTH_NEEDS_ADMINISTRATIVE__: The Town receives quarterly reports from Trinity ambulance; this report breaks down data regarding overdoses by day of the week, time of day, town/location, and age.
BEHAVIORAL_HEALTH_NEEDS_BARRIERS__C: The Town uses the Connections website to break down the social stigma surrounding mental health and seeking assistance for mental health issues. The Town also provides psychosocial services.
BEHAVIORAL_HEALTH_NEEDS_OTHER__C: The Town is a member of a coalition that uses a psychiatric Frontline and Credible Minds to reach out to users and refer them to services and treatment. The Town also follows up with children whose parents or guardians have overdosed.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS_ON_MA_OPIOID_INIT__C: Please note this report is being submitted on behalf of the 15 towns in the Cooperative Public Health Service Health District, located at the Franklin Regional Council of Governments.  The dollar figures reporting in the Erving report are just Erving's but the work to plan has all been regional, and expenses will begin in Fall 2024.  The towns are: Ashfield, Bernardston, Buckland, Charlemont, Colrain, Conway, Erving, Gill, Hawley, Heath, Leyden, Northfield, Monroe, Rowe, and Shelburne
BARRIERS_TO_IDENTIFYING_DISPARITIES__C: In a rural area our population is small, and our BIPOC population is very small (under 10% of adults), so getting reliable data from state sources is nearly impossible (they will not report small numbers). Similarly no one that reports on OUD treatment do

BARRIERS_TO_OUD_TREATMENT__C: The 15 rural towns reporting in Erving's portal do not receive enough funding to provide treatment services.

BEHAVIORAL_HEALTH_NEEDS_BARRIERS__C: The 15 towns that Erving is reporting for, members of the Cooperative Public Health District, are getting so little funding (on  average under $34K/year) that we do not have enough to make a difference on co-occurring disorders.

BARRIERS_TO_OPIOID_MISUSE_AND_PREVENTION: The Clinician through Eliot that works with Police does an outstanding job- they must work over three towns and there just is not enough capacity for once person to connect with everyone. The Eliot position could be for Concord only.

ADDITIONAL_COMMENTS_ON_MA_OPIOID_INIT__C: Thank you for the opportunity to complete this report. Due to new public health leadership this FY and the small size of our health department, it has taken some time to begin the process of spending these funds. We are pleased that we now have some needs assessment data and that we have executed a few contracts in FY 24 with a partner organization serving a marginalized population at disproportionate risk for opioid overdose. We look forward to reporting on the results of our partner's efforts,
ADMINISTRATIVE_ALREADY_REIMBURSED__C: N/A
BARRIERS_FOR_PEOPLE_IN_TX_AND_RECOVERY__: We have made connections to Recovery groups at UMass Amherst and plan to work this FY to increase access to peer recovery services for others in the broader Amherst community.  The main barrier has been lack of time on the part of Health Department staff
BARRIERS_TO_CONNECTIONS_TO_CARE__C: Amherst has a DART (Drug Addiction Recovery Team) program housed within its Police Department. Because the DART lead was out on medical leave for some of FY24 and because the Health Director is new in her role, collaboration to strengthen and expand the t
BARRIERS_TO_HARM_REDUCTION__C: No funds were actually expended in FY24 but two contracts were executed in FY24 with the Amherst shelter - Craig's Doors - to support training for shelter staff on the use of narcan and CPR to assist in the event of an overdose, and for the purchase of ha
BARRIERS_TO_IDENTIFYING_DISPARITIES__C: We partnered with Hampshire HOPE to conduct a survey in the region which yielded some helpful data about community priorities for spending of the opioid funds. However, the vast majority of the respondents from our town were white. In Amherst, there are s
BARRIERS_TO_JUSTICE_INVOLVED_PERSONS__C: This has not so far been identified as a need in Amherst. We plan to have further conversations with the community to understand the prevalence of those impacted by the criminal justice system and to assess and address their needs.
BARRIERS_TO_OUD_TREATMENT__C: There are few if any OUD treatment resources in Amherst. We plan to work with our local opioid task force - Hampshire HOPE - this fiscal year to assess, expand and promote regional treatment resources in the area.
BARRIERS_TO_OPIOID_MISUSE_AND_PREVENTION: Collaboration with the schools was complicated in FY 24 due to internal challenges that the school administration was facing. We hope that under the new administration, we can begin exploring ways to plan and implement activities to prevent substance misu
BARRIERS_TO_PREGNANT_AND_PARENTING_WOMEN: This work currently falls outside of the scope of the Health Department since it does not work directly with pregnant individuals or new families. We are part of a Shared Service Collaborative that has planned some interventions for pregnant women and new

BEHAVIORAL_HEALTH_NEEDS_BARRIERS__C: We lack easily accessible sources of local data regarding mental health conditions, number of patients in treatment etc. Hope to collaborate with other municipalities in our SSA to assess these date collaboratively in the region.
